  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most countries and is typically addressed under criminal legislation. Key points include:\n\n1. Legal classification\n- Considered a serious financial crime\n- Prosecuted under criminal law\n- Carries potential criminal penalties and sanctions\n\n2. Typical legal frameworks\n- Anti-Money Laundering (AML) laws\n- Criminal codes\n- Financial regulatory statutes\n\n3. Criminal consequences\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Asset seizure\n- Criminal record\n\n4. International standards\n- Most countries have laws criminalizing money laundering\n- United Nations and FATF (Financial Action Task Force) provide global guidelines\n- Coordinated international legal efforts to combat the practice\n\n5. Common legal elements\n- Intentional concealment of illegal funds\n- Transforming \"dirty\" money into seemingly legitimate assets\n- Disguising the source of illicit income\n\nMoney laundering is treated as a criminal offense due to its association with underlying criminal activities like drug trafficking, fraud, and organized crime.",
